<br>
Quote (1) ----------------------------------------------------<br>
“Exploration for scientific purposes can be better (and <br>
far more cheaply) carried out by fleets of unmanned probes”<br>
<br>
Quote (2) ----------------------------------------------------<br>
“The practical case for manned space-flight gets ever-weaker <br>
with each advance in robotics and miniaturization.”<br>
<br>
BETTER THAN MANNED MISSIONS:<br>
<br>
The Astronomer Royal’s statements that I have quoted lead me to suspect that his opinions are severely tainted by his tenure in the ivory towers of academia. Most residents of academia are of the opinion that interplanetary flight serves only as a method of remote data collection to further their particular disciplines (this is especially true of astronomers). If these expensive by proxy field trips to remote areas of the solar system serve only to further the intellectual activities of the ‘Intelligencia’ then they have no real value.<br>
<br>
First of all It must be remembered that It is not a necessity at this time to do anything in space except maintain the worlds communication and weather satellites and keep an eye on earth crossing asteroids. While robotic exploration may return information that thrills members of the scientific community to the nth degree the fact remains that not one item of information returned has had any real positive effect on the human condition.<br>
<br>
The long term goal of space flight must be to improve in some way the lives of the common people that are footing the bill for these expensive ventures. The acquisition of obscure facts and knowledge is not a sufficient reason to pay the high cost of exploring the solar system there must be a genuine pay off. <br>
<br>
Dr. Reec maintains that ‘fleets’ of unmanned probes can ‘explore’ the solar system better than manned missions. His supposition is absurd. For one thing unmanned probes are far from cheap, and they are prone to complete failure from trivial malfunctions. Additionally their ability to gather valuable information is extremely limited. <br>
<br>
The Astronomer Royal’s suppositions lean heavily on the development of “intelligent’ probes that can make decisions in lieu of timely command signals from mission control. <br>
<br>
The question is, just how smart are computers? The current state of AI is far behind the expectations and hopes of the computer science community. Today we are as far from developing a HAL 9000 computer as we were in 1968 when the movie 2001 was made. Apparently processing power and machine intelligence are not as closely linked as the computer science folks once imagined or hoped them to be. <br>
<br>
The failure of computer science to produce a single piece of software than can pass the ‘Turning Test’(1) is proof of how pathetic current machine intelligence is when compared to human intelligence. The very best we can do at this point in time is make the mechanical equivalent of an idiot savant with a razor thin area of expertise. <br>
<br>
Computers never have an epiphany or an original thought, neither can they react to situations the programmers didn’t foresee. A computer loaded with an AI program still just receives an input and then generates an output based on the searching through lists to find a match. The computer is just doing what it does best comparing, matching, parsing, and calculating it is incapable of thinking. <br>
<br>
(1)   <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://cogsci.ucsd.edu/~asaygin/tt/ttest.html#intro">cogsci.ucsd.edu/~asaygin/...html#intro</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
An example of the inherently stupid behavior of a ‘computerized explorer’ is to be found in the recent failure of the ‘Mars Polar Lander’. The cause of its impact on to the Martian surface has been determined to be premature shutdown of the descent thrusters. Apparently the on board computer misinterpreted the shock caused by the deployment of its landing gear to be the shock associated with touch down on the Martian surface. The result of that error is that our imbecilic $159,000,000.00 computerized explorer fell unchecked from an altitude of several thousand feet to become a very expensive grease spot on the Martin landscape. The data return of this expensive little idiot was ZERO. Obviously no human pilot could conceivably make such a moronic error unless he was blind, drunk and suffering from dementia.<br>
<br>
I firmly believe that robotic exploration is not in any way comparable to human exploration in either the quantity and quality of the information returned. I also maintain that is it not as cost effective in the long run.<br>
<br>
<br>
THE COST OF UNMANNED MISSIONS:<br>
<br>
A 600kg unmanned interplanetary probe requires an onboard computer, a complete 3D gyroscopic platform navigation system, the ability to correct its course and attitude, long range communication , command signal processing capabilities, sensors, instrument packages, experiments, descent thrusters, an electrical  power source, and lastly an expensive booster such as a  $60,000,000.00 Delta-7925 that must be expended to put it on an intercept trajectory with its target. These probes also need a sizable support team on Earth and the assistance of a global tracking system. <br>
<br>
The cost for typical NASA interplanetary probe is generally 150 to 300 million dollars. Taking the mean value as the price tag and adding the cost of the booster we come up with  $225,000,000.00 + $60,000,000.00 = $285,000,000.00. The journey to Mars takes about a year and the attention of about 100 people that receive an average of $70,000.00/annum (low estimate). That’s another $7,000,000.00 so the figure for the complete mission is around $292,000,000.00. <br>
<br>
The Mars Polar Lander that I have used as a model was expected to remain active for three months before freezing to death. So the cost of operation would have turned out to be about $135,000.00 dollars for every hour spent on Mars actively ‘exploring’ the surrounding patch of Martian dirt. During that time it would have taken thousands of pictures (that’s pretty neat) and evaluated the composition of a few pounds of alien soil. Please excuses me for not being particularly impressed with this type of exploration.   <br>
<br>
Now that NASA has abandoned their mantra of ‘faster, cheaper, better’ (did they ever accomplish that goal even once?) we can expect a sharp rise in the cost (50% at the minimum) of such probes. <br>
<br>
If NASA were to as Dr. Reec suggests put their shoulders to the grindstone and launch a ‘fleet’ of such probes at Mars at the rate of five per year for five years. The price tag would be at the new higher cost level  $438,000,000 per probe. That gives us a 5 year  program at a cost of  (($438,000,000) x( 5)^2 = $10,950,000,000.00. Realistically  a 2% cost increase per year would be normal so the bill would be 11.3 billion dollars. <br>
<br>
If the entire ‘fleet’ of unmanned probes functioned perfectly how much of Mars would have been explored? Assuming that 15 of these probes were Landers with a pivoting arm could extend 3 meters to get a sample and rotate that arm through a 90 deg arc each probe could work an area of  7 square meters. That would be a total of 105 square meters of the Martian surface explored and sampled for a cost of $64,500,000.00 per square meter for those landers. <br>
<br>
The remaining 10 landers could be armed with one mini rover each with the ability to sample 500 times the area of the fixed Landers ( I am being very generous here). In that case those 10 missions could sample 35000 square meters at a cost of  $130,000.00 per square meter. <br>
<br>
In the end we would have sampled 35105 square meters in five years for a cost of  approximately $320,000.00 per square meter. Again considering the vast investment involved excuse me for not being overly impressed by a five year long eleven billion dollar program that explored and directly sampled an area of Mars that totals up to be about the size of 8 football fields.<br>
<br>
 THE SUPERIORITY OF MANNED EXPLORATION<br>
<br>
What could we accomplish If we were to forgo the launching of Dr. Reec’s ‘fleet’ of unmanned probes and instead spend the 11.3 billion dollars on building a reusable 400 ton nuclear powered spacecraft for a manned Earth orbit to Mars orbit mission? <br>
<br>
The ship could easily devote 40 tons of its mass to a vast array of relatively simple and truly cheap instrument packages that could be landed on the Martian surface. Some of these Landers could  have the same functional capabilities as vehicles like the Mars Polar Lander but they would be cheaper and lighter because they wouldn’t need all the machinery and fuel that is devoted to interplanetary navigation, and course correction. The simple vehicles could be flown down to the surface with the assistance of a human pilot sitting in front of a computer screen inside the mother ship (much like military RPV’s). <br>
<br>
Assuming that each large lander including its heat shield and aero-shell weighed 500 Kilograms The ship could carry 50 of these at a cost of 27.5 tons of the total payload. These RPV-landers could also have more mass devoted to a larger and more powerful source of electricity to facilitate a longer period of operation. <br>
<br>
The remaining 12.5 tons could be devoted to placing six 1000 pound GPS /communications relay/ and ground observation satellites in geo-synchronous orbits around Mars. The last  9.5 tons could be devoted to ‘scatterable’ sensors and single use sampling devises. These could be patterned after military  air dropped remote sensors in use today.  If each remote sensor had a weight of 20 pounds then more than 900 of them could be dumped on the Martian Landscape in patterns of 30. Each ‘bomblet’ would have a miniaturized transmitter that sends its location using the GPS satellites as a reference along with its individual and array ID numbers plus the results of its single experiment to the comsats in orbit. The data would  then be recorded organized and transmitted to Earth for analysis.<br>
<br>
The best thing is that all this could be done under the direct control of human beings capable of swift intervention to avert and compensate for mishaps.<br>
<br>
NukePulse  <br>
<br>
PS: To borrow Dr. Reec’s analogy of Captain Cook’s voyage of discovery sending unmanned probes into interplanetary space to do the work of human beings is like<br>
Captain Cook exploring uncharted islands by sending rowboats to them with his dumbest crewmen at the helms and expecting them to send smoke signals back to describe what they have observed. <br>
